## Preface

### Genesis of the Book

- **July 1993**: Bernstein discovered *Wall Street Journal* article ("Your Money Matters")
on asset allocation performance 1973–92 from **T. Rowe Price** research
- Study constructed imaginary portfolios from U.S. large/small stocks, foreign stocks,
U.S. bonds—calculated returns and risks over 20 years
- **Key finding**: Various fixed mixes of the four assets outperformed single component
parts (including professional money managers) with significantly lower risk

### The "Simpleton's Portfolio"

- Equal 25% allocation to U.S. large stocks, U.S. small stocks, foreign stocks,
U.S. high-quality bonds
- Higher return and much lower risk than large U.S. stocks alone (S&P 500)
- **S&P 500 outperformed 75% of professional money managers** over same period

### Historical Research Project

- No readily available software existed for historical asset allocation backtesting
- Bernstein built spreadsheet models going back to **1926**
- Collected data on wide variety of assets across multiple historical epochs
- **Critical assumption**: portfolios were **rebalanced** periodically
- Rebalancing required because some assets outperform others, altering original composition

### Asset Allocation vs. Stock Picking

- Experienced investors learn: coherent allocation strategy is key to long-term success
- **Market timing and stock/fund picking are nearly impossible long-term**
- Far more important to get right proportion of foreign stocks, U.S. stocks,
foreign bonds, U.S. bonds than to pick "best" stocks or time markets

> "Nobody consistently calls the market, and almost nobody picks stocks or mutual funds with any persistent skill."

### Historical Evidence: 1987, 1992, 1995–1998

- **1987**: U.S. large stocks +5.23%, small stocks −9.3%, foreign stocks +24.93%
- **1992**: U.S. small stocks +23.35%, foreign stocks −11.85%
- **1995–1998**: Unprecedented returns for biggest U.S. growth stocks,
battered almost everything else

### Gary Brinson Studies (Late 1980s)

- **Gary Brinson** and colleagues studied 82 large pension funds
- **Asset allocation accounted for over 90% of return variability** among funds
- Less-than-10% contribution from market timing and actual stock/bond selection

> "In other words, asset allocation policy was 10 times as important as stock picking and market timing combined."

- Some observers suggest 90% figure too high—perhaps only 50%
- Misses the point: market timing and security selection obviously important,
but **nobody achieves long-term success** in former, almost nobody in latter

> "Asset allocation is the only factor affecting your investments that you can actually influence."

### Media Focus on Wrong Things

- Enormous ink/airtime wasted on analysts' predictions of stock/bond price direction
and particular stock/fund recommendations
- **Louis Rukeyser's *Wall Street Week* (1994)**: Brinson's comments almost entirely
on market timing, almost no attention to asset allocation strategy
- Gambling instinct ingrained in human nature—few resist speculation

### How to Arrive at Optimal Allocation

- **You can't determine the perfect allocation**—but neither can anyone else
- Not even **Mr. Brinson** had more assets under management than any other individual
on the planet
- Can examine *what has worked in the past* but don't confuse with *what will work
in the future*
- Historical lessons are sparse but valuable

### Three Lessons from History

1. **Stocks are riskier than cash**
2. **In the future, stocks will probably have higher returns than cash, but not by
as much as in the past**
3. **Portfolio diversification reduces risk**
4. **Index your investments wherever you can**

### The "Simpleton's Portfolio" Recipe

If tired of reading, simple recipe: Purchase index funds—one quarter each of U.S.
large stocks, U.S. small stocks, foreign stocks, short-term U.S. bond fund

- Index funds commoditized like computer chips and gasoline
- Available through most large fund families and "supermarkets"
- Highly recommends **Vanguard**
- **Rebalance annually** so each of four parts returns to equal size
- Setup: ~15 minutes; annual rebalancing: ~15 minutes
- If next 20 years like last 20, will outperform portfolios of 75% of professional managers

### Efficient Frontier Website (1996)

- Placed book's first edition online at **http://www.efficientfrontier.com**
- Reaction exceeded expectations—small investors hungry for asset allocation
and portfolio theory information
- Investment professionals also responded—acknowledged importance but lacked
roadmap for implementation
- Magic of Internet: contacted dozens sharing fascination with portfolio theory
- Electronic editions followed, revised based on website discussions

### Changes in Print Edition

- **Stronger emphasis on indexing**—active portfolio management is "sucker's game"
- Small stocks, REITs, foreign stocks: active managers appear to do well but
**outperformance is illusory**
- Eliminated most manual calculation sections—spreadsheets and financial calculators
made manual techniques obsolete
- New algorithm for rebalanced portfolio returns; abandoned spreadsheet optimization
from previous versions

### Electronic Commerce Revolution

- Investment industry embraced electronic commerce—dizzying variety of tools and
vehicles available
- Unfortunately, most is rope to hang yourself: fund supermarkets, on-line trading,
enormous volume of securities "research"
- **For prudent investor, benefits abound**: explosion of Internet services,
brightest minds in modern finance available to anyone with computer/modem/phone line
- **Proliferation of inexpensive indexed investment vehicles**—now even smallest
investors can build portfolios as efficiently as biggest players

### Acknowledgments

Thanks to **Jonathan Clements, Robert Barker, Frank Armstrong, John Rekenthaler,
David Wilkinson, Steve Dunn, Scott Burns** and others for advice over the years

Special gratitude to **Susan Sharin** for unique money-management skills and financial
knowledge

Greatest thanks to wife **Jane** for encouragement and editing support

