## Chapter 1: General Considerations

### Uncle Fred's Pension Plan

Uncle Fred is conscientious employer—after years of service, lets you in on company
pension plan

- 30 years old, will work for uncle until retire in 35 years at age 65
- Each year contributes $5000 to retirement account
- Must pick ahead of time one of two investment choices for duration of employment:

**Option 1**: Certificates of deposit with 3% annualized rate of return

**Option 2**: Most peculiar option—at end of each year Uncle Fred flips coin.
Heads = 30% investment return for that year; tails = −10% (loss) for year.
Referred to as **"Uncle Fred's coin toss"** or simply "coin toss"

### Evaluating Option 1

- Fixed rate of return, absolutely certain lump sum at end of 35 years
- Financial calculator shows yields $302,310
- Inflation will diminish future value of princely sum
- If inflation 3%, left with only $107,436 of current spending power

### Evaluating Option 2: The Coin Toss

- Thought of losing 10% of hard-earned retirement money with coin loss is too much
to bear
- What if string of losing years? Get tails all 35 years = only pittance for retirement
- If heads all 35 years, bankrupt poor Uncle Fred with $162,000,000 gain

### Analyzing the Coin Toss More Carefully

Over long enough period, will get exactly half heads and half tails

- If alternating series of heads and tails, return in each two-year period
represented by: **1.3 × 0.9 = 1.17**
- First year 30% return multiplies account by 1.3; 10% loss multiplies by 0.9
- For each dollar at beginning of two-year period, now have $1.17

### Annualized Return Calculation

17% return at end of two years = same as annual return of **8.17%**

- Clearly superior to 3% return of first option
- Could have string of bad luck and get tails more than half the time
- With trial and error on calculator: would have to get **12 heads and 23 tails**
before coming out worse than first option
- Odds of this quite low

### The Binomial Distribution

Visit former college statistics professor, who chides for forgetting could easily
calculate odds with **binomial distribution function**

- Your blank look elicits sigh, he pulls up spreadsheet program
- After few keystrokes hands graph in **Figure 1-1**
- **Odds of flipping less than 13 heads and coming out behind: Less than 5%**

### Order of Coin Tosses Matters

The *order* of coin tosses matters a great deal

- Toss 16 straight heads then 19 straight tails: will still come out behind
- Toss 27 straight tails followed by 8 straight heads: will actually come out ahead
- These are extremely unlikely events
- Preceding formulation and graph in Figure 1-1 are accurate representation of odds
in your favor

### Average vs. Annualized Return

Coin toss introduces difference between **average** and **annualized** return

- Some may wonder why return of coin toss not 10% instead of 8.17%
- Average of +30% and −10% is +10% (30 minus 10, divided by 2)
- **Average return**: simply average of each individual annual returns
- **Annualized return**: more subtle concept—return you must earn each and every
year to equal result of your series of differing annual returns

### Example: Stock Doubles Then Loses 50%

Own stock which doubles (100% return) first year then loses 50% next year =
zero annualized return

- Stock worth $10 per share at start
- Worth $20 at end of first year
- $10 again at end of second year
- Made no money, yet *average* return is 25% (average of +100% and −50%)
- **Annualized return is zero**

### Key Distinction

Annualized and average return clearly are not the same

- Coin toss has average return of 10% and annualized return of 8.17%
- **Annualized return is always less than average return**
- If coin toss comes up with half −10% and half +30% returns, same as having
8.17% return each and every year
- **You pay bills with annualized return, not average return**—why annualized
returns so important

### Uncle Fred's Coin Toss Mirrors Real Investing

Uncle Fred's coin toss may seem bizarre scenario, yet nearly identical to choice
most investors face between "safety" of money market accounts/Treasury bills and
"gamble" of common stocks

- Second option offers near certainty of superior result, yet comes at price
- Small possibility of inferior result and, more importantly, that gut-wrenching
coin toss session with Uncle Fred each year
- 3% certificate of deposit option is most truly frightening—**will almost certainly
live golden years in poverty**

### Construction of Uncle Fred's Coin Toss

Constructed coin toss with deliberation—easy to grasp and quite closely approximates
returns and risks of common stocks

- Return of common stocks over past 73 years (1926–1998) was **11.22%**, in same
league as coin toss
- More importantly, **"riskiness" of coin toss and common stocks are nearly identical**
- Shall explain shortly how to measure precisely this riskiness
- Coin toss is handy symbolic representation of risks and returns of common stocks
- Will provide powerful way to understand behavior of portfolios with multiple asset types

### First Fundamental Law of Investing

Just been introduced to one of fundamental laws of investing:

> **In the long run you are compensated for bearing risk. Conversely, if you seek safety, your returns will be low.**

- Experienced investors understand reward and risk are inextricably intertwined
- One of most reliable ways to spot investment fraud is promise of excessive returns
with low risk

### Example: Asset A Returns Over Eight Years

Consider example slightly more complex than coin toss

Say invested in asset A (doesn't matter what it is). Returns for eight consecutive
years as follows:

