## Fund Recommendations (continued)

### Vanguard Global Index Concerns
- Vanguard's asset-allocation funds (Wellesley, Wellington, Asset Allocation, Life Strategies, STAR, Global Asset Allocation) are grossly underweighted in foreign and small stocks
- Author does not recommend any of these funds
- Vanguard may eventually create an "everything index fund" now that **John Bogle** (who dislikes foreign assets) has retired

### Tweedy, Browne Recommendation (with caveats)
- Long record of consistent value investing
- Could split investments between their American and Global Value funds
- Distinguished record in private money management, but only ~6 years in mutual fund business
- Expenses fairly high — use only in tax-sheltered accounts
- Previous edition recommended **Soken International** and **Mutual Discovery**:
  - Soken has fallen flat
  - Mutual Discovery lost star manager **Mike Price**, acquired by **Franklin Resources**
- History suggests actively managed funds eventually disappoint

### Keeping Abreast of Market Valuation

- **Dynamic asset allocation** (Chapter 7): changing policy allocation based on valuations
- Don't try at home unless successfully rebalanced through multiple market cycles
- Increase allocation to an asset only after it's gotten measurably cheaper and been hammered in price
- Never increase allocation based on economic/political events or analyst recommendations
- Same rule for decreasing: do so only because valuations have gotten much higher after major run-up

### Monitoring Valuation Metrics

**Morningstar Principia database** provides easiest access to valuation data:
- P/E, P/C (price/cash flow), P/B, dividend yield for index funds

**Key index funds to monitor:**
- Vanguard 500 Index (S&P 500)
- Vanguard Value Index / Growth Index
- Vanguard Small-Cap Growth/Value Index
- Vanguard Small-Cap Index (Russell 2000)
- Vanguard Extended Market Index (Wilshire 4500)
- Vanguard Total Market Index (Wilshire 5000)
- Vanguard European Stock Index (EAFE-Europe)
- Vanguard Pacific Stock Index (EAFE-Pacific)
- Vanguard Emerging Markets Stock Index (MSCI-EM)
- DFA U.S. 9-10 Small Company
- DFA U.K./Japanese/Continental/Pacific Rim/Emerging Markets Small Company

**Barra's website** provides valuation parameters for domestic (not foreign) assets
- P/B and dividend yield are most stable measurements
- P/E and P/C less useful
- Dividend yield is only measure with meaning across different stock asset classes

### Current Market Valuation (as of book publication)

**"How expensive are the tomatoes right now?"**

- S&P 500 P/B currently 10.5 — never been remotely this high except once before in 1929
- Dividend yield at record low 1.3%
- Historical data on U.S. small stocks and foreign large stocks doesn't go back far
- Small cap P/B ~3, foreign P/B ~4 — probably very high by historical standards
- Small foreign stocks seem cheaper at P/B 2.4 (but limited historical data)

> "Many now assert that P/B and dividend yield have become irrelevant. However, at market highs, one always hears arguments about how the old valuation measures don't matter any more."

**John Templeton's admonition:**
> "The four most expensive words in the English language are 'this time it's different.'"

Author adds the five dumbest words: "The bull market remains intact."

## Retirement—The Biggest Risk of All

### Duration Risk Explained

**One-year Treasury bill example:**
- 5% bill sells at $0.9524, redeemed at $1
- If yields suddenly rise to 10%, bill falls to $0.9091 — immediate 4.55% loss
- But investor holding to maturity still gets full 5% return
- After one year, can reinvest at double the yield
- **Point of indifference:** one-year maturity — before one year worse off, after one year better off

**30-year 5% Treasury bond example:**
- If yields rise to 10% soon after purchase, bond drops to less than 53 cents on dollar
- Almost entire value represented by 5% coupon payments, worth only half at current 10% market yield
- This happened to bondholders 1967-1979
- Bond throws off coupons that can be reinvested at higher yield
- Recovery takes considerably less than 30 years
- Investor breaks even in **10.96 years** — this is the **duration**
- **Duration** always less than **maturity** for coupon-bearing bonds (equal for zero-coupon)

**Technical definition of duration:**
- Ratio of price-to-yield change
- 30-year bond decreases 10.96% in price with each 1% increase in yield

> "After 10.96 years, our unlucky bondholder is better off for the fall in price because of the rise in yield."

- Duration measures investment risk — higher duration = bigger risk

### Duration Applied to Stocks

- Duration concept applies to stocks, not just bonds
- Stocks currently yielding ~1.3%
- If stocks decline 75%, absolute dividend amount stays same, but now investing dividends at yield 4x higher (5.2%)
- Eventually this redounds to benefit — wind up better off than at lower yield and higher price

**Duration scenarios at 1.3% stock yield:**
- 25% decline = 63 years duration
- 50% decline = 51 years
- 75% decline = 33 years
- 90% decline = only 19 years

**Reality check: 1929-1945 bear market**
- $1 invested Labor Day 1929 → 16.6 cents by Independence Day 1932
- Increased back to par by end of January 1945 — less than 13 years after bottom
- Dividend yield 2.6% in September 1929
- For 30 years after, earnings growth only 1.8%
- Had crash not occurred, stocks would have returned 4.4%/year
- Break-even in January 1952 (22 years later) — almost exactly duration model prediction

**Today's market more frightening than 1929:**
- 75% stock decline at 2.6% 1929 yield = 19 years duration
- Same decline at current 1.3% yield = 33 years duration

> "Certainly, such a wrenching market decline today would wreak havoc on the financial and social structure of the republic, as it did 70 years ago. But at the same time, today's high prices and resultant low yields are no great blessing either. This is because the lower the coupon or dividend yield, the longer the duration. Thus, the lower the yield, the higher the market price; the longer the duration, the greater the risk."

### Shortening Duration Through Contributions

- Can effectively increase yield of portfolio by adding to it every month
- Example: 1.3% yield, 75% price fall, 33-year duration scenario
- $10,000 initial with no additions = break even at 33 years
- $10,000 + $200/month additions = break even at just over 11 years

**Retirees face opposite problem:**
- Cannot shorten duration with additional investment
- Can be devastated if duration of holdings is longer than retirement horizon

### Duration and Time Horizon

**Paradoxical reality:**
- Long-term investor: prolonged bear/bull market may prove of little consequence or even produce surprisingly paradoxical results
- Equanimity to market declines depends on time horizon
- **Retired and living off savings:** neither enough time to get over duration hump nor ability to make contributions to shorten it
- **Boomer still adding to nest egg:** likely plenty of time
- **Twenty-something just beginning:** get down on knees and pray for market crash

**Investment pain types:**
- Short-term: brutal bear markets lighten portfolio
- Long-term: **shortfall risk** — running out of money before death

> "After all, most of us are saving and investing for a purpose, usually retirement, or some other well-defined future financial need. The ivory-tower types refer to this as shortfall risk, and it's worth a few pages of consideration."

(Reference to **Chapter 7** discussion of how investors obsess on short-term risks while ignoring more important longer-term picture)

### Retirement Calculations

**Before-tax needs:**
- Assume need for $40,000 annual income (in addition to Social Security)
- Simplify by using **real** (inflation-adjusted) returns
- Always dealing with current, constant purchasing-power dollars
- Reasonable estimate for real return of mixed stock/bond portfolio: **~4%**
- Can spend 4% of portfolio each year while maintaining real value indefinitely
- Can also maintain portfolio's real value indefinitely while maintaining real value of withdrawals
- $1,000,000 in assets needed (4% of $1,000,000 = $40,000)

**Formula:** Required savings = income requirement / real investment return = $40,000 / 0.04 = $1,000,000

**If willing to expire with zero assets:**
- Using annuity/mortgage function on financial calculator (Texas Instruments BA-35, ~$20)
- Required savings only $691,681 for 30 years

### The Expense Problem

- 4% return assumption refers to **market return**
- Investment fees and expenses must be subtracted
- Typical 401(k) with 1%-2% total expenses means you may need up to 2x as much ($40,000/0.02 = $2,000,000) in retirement savings
- **2% of additional costs translates into doubling of retirement savings requirement**

> "This kind of calculation emphasizes the extreme importance of attention to expense—in this situation, 2% of additional costs translates into a doubling of your retirement savings requirement."

### The Sequence-of-Returns Problem

**Critical issue:** retirement calculators assume same return each and every year
- In reality, returns vary year to year
- **Order of good and bad years matters a great deal**

**Uncle Fred's coin toss example** (−10% or +30% returns):
- Over 30 years: 15 heads, 15 tails = compounded 8.17%
- Starting with $1,000,000, rolling alternating heads/tails over 30 years:
  - Can withdraw $81,700 annually (8.17% of initial) for next 30 years and keep $1,000,000 principal intact
- **15 straight tails before 15 straight heads:** can withdraw only $18,600/year before money runs out
- **15 straight heads followed by 15 tails:** can withdraw $248,600/year
- **In saving phase:** much better off having bad years at beginning, bull market later

### Trinity University Study

**Philip L. Cooley, Carl M. Hubbard, and Daniel T. Walz** from Trinity University:
- Looked at "success rate" of various withdrawal strategies over numerous historical periods
- Conclusion: only 4%-5% withdrawal rate of initial portfolio value had reasonable expectation of success (dying without debt)
- Based on historical data with 7% real equity returns

### 1966-1995 Retirement Stress Test

**Acid test:** retiring January 1, 1966, living until December 31, 1995
- First 17 years (1966-1982): S&P 500 return was paltry 6.81%
- By numerical coincidence, identical to inflation rate — real stock return for whole 1966-1982 period was **zero**
- Next 13 years (1983-1995): spectacular, bringing real return for whole 30-year 1966-1995 period up to 5.4%

**Withdrawal rate simulations** (starting with $1,000,000):
- Portfolio: 80% S&P 500 + 20% U.S. small stocks, mixed with 5-year Treasuries
- Various mixes tested: 100% stock, 100% bond, 75/25, 50/50, 25/75
- Withdrawal rates tested: 7%, 6%, 5%, 4% (annually withdrawing $70,000, $60,000, $50,000, $40,000)
- Results plotted in **Figures 8-1 through 8-4**
- All-stock portfolio = thickest line; thinner line = less stock
- All amounts in **inflation-adjusted 1966 dollars**
